1 aid in the discovery or apprehension of an offender; or
2 (f) aids an offender who is subject to official detention to escape from official detention.
3 (3) A person convicted of obstructing justice shall be:
4 (a) imprisoned in the state prison for a term not to exceed 10 years if the offender has been or is
5 liable to be charged with a felony; or
6 (b) fined not to exceed $500 or be imprisoned in the county jail for a term not to exceed 6 months,
7 or both, if the offender has been or is liable to be charged with a misdemeanor."
8
9 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Appropriation. There is appropriated $500 from the general fund to the
10 department of justice for the biennium beginning July 1, 2025, for the purpose of notifying police departments,
11 sheriff's offices, local law enforcement agencies, and county attorneys by mail about the requirements of [this
12 act].
